<appendix id="sec.blas_lapack_inst">
  <title id="title.blas_lapack_inst">
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym>( or <acronym>ATLAS</acronym>), and
    <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> Installation
  </title>

  <para>
    <acronym>PETSc</acronym> requires <acronym>BLAS</acronym>, or its
    equivalent <acronym>ATLAS</acronym>, and
    <acronym>LAPACK</acronym>.
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>ATLAS</acronym> and
    <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> must be installed before installing
    <acronym>PETSc</acronym>.  A vendor version of
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>ATLAS</acronym> is recommended.
    Skip this section if
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>ATLAS</acronym> and
    <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> are installed.  There is no need to
    install <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>ATLAS</acronym> or
    <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> on a &osx; system.  &osx; users can skip
    to <xref linkend="sec.petsc"/>.
  </para>

  <para>
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> can be
    installed from <link
    linkend="sec.blas_lapack_rpm"><acronym>RPM</acronym>'s
    (Linux)</link> or a combined
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> <link
    linkend="sec.blas_lapack_source">source distribution (SGI)</link>.
    Linux users should install the <acronym>RPM</acronym>s.
  </para>

  <para>
    <ulink
    url="http://math-atlas.sourceforge.net/"><acronym>ATLAS</acronym></ulink>
    is a portable <acronym>BLAS</acronym> implementation.
    <acronym>ATLAS</acronym> can be installed in place of
    <acronym>BLAS</acronym>.  <acronym>ATLAS</acronym> should be
    installed from its <link linkend="sec.atlas_source">source
    code distribution</link>.
  </para>

  <section id="sec.blas_lapack_rpm">
    <title id="title.blas_lapack_rpm"><acronym>RPM</acronym>s
    (Linux)</title>
    <para>
      Root privileges are needed to install the
      <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and <acronym>LAPACK</acronym>
      <acronym>RPM</acronym>s.
    </para>
    <para>
      Use a browser to download <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and
      <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> <acronym>RPM</acronym>s for Linux:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
<ulink url="http://www.netlib.org/lapack/rpms/lapack-3_0-2_i386.rpm">http://www.netlib.org/lapack/rpms/lapack-3_0-2_i386.rpm</ulink> 
      </literallayout>
      and
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
<ulink url="http://www.netlib.org/lapack/rpms/blas-3_0-2_i386.rpm">http://www.netlib.org/lapack/rpms/blas-3_0-2_i386.rpm</ulink>
      </literallayout>
    </para>
    <para>
      Become root user:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
su -
      </literallayout>
      and install the <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and <acronym>LAPACK</acronym>
      <acronym>RPM</acronym>s:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
rpm -ivh blas-3_0-2_i386.rpm
rpm -ivh lapack-3_0-2_i386.rpm
      </literallayout>
      Type <command>exit</command> to leave the root account.
    </para>
  </section>

  <section id="sec.blas_lapack_source">
    <title id="title.blas_lapack_source">Source Code (SGI)</title>

    <para>
      Follow these steps to install <acronym>BLAS</acronym> and
      <acronym>LAPACK</acronym> from the combined source distribution:
      <orderedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Download the source distribution:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
<ulink url="ftp://ftp.mcs.anl.gov/pub/petsc/fblaslapack.tar.gz">ftp://ftp.mcs.anl.gov/pub/petsc/fblaslapack.tar.gz</ulink>
	    </literallayout>
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Unpack the <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>LAPACK</acronym>
	    distribution:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
gunzip -c fblaslapack.tar.gz | tar xvf -
	    </literallayout>
	    This creates the <filename>fblaslapack</filename> directory.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Build <acronym>BLAS</acronym>/<acronym>LAPACK</acronym>:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
cd fblaslapack
make
	    </literallayout>
	    This creates libraries <filename>libfblas.a</filename> and
	    <filename>liblapack.a</filename> in directory
	    <filename>fblaslapack</filename>.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
      </orderedlist>
    </para>
  </section>

  <section id="sec.atlas_source">
    <title id="title.atlas_source"><acronym>ATLAS</acronym> (Linux, SGI)</title>
    <para>
      Follow these steps to install <acronym>ATLAS</acronym>:
      <orderedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Download the source distribution:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
<ulink url="https://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=23725">https://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=23725</ulink>
	    </literallayout>
	    Choose from the list of files a stable, 
	    platform-independent distribution,
	    e.g. <filename>atlas3.6.0.tar.gz</filename>.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Unpack the <acronym>ATLAS</acronym> distribution:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
gunzip -c atlas<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz | tar xvf -
	    </literallayout>
	    This creates a directory named <filename>ATLAS</filename>.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Build <acronym>ATLAS</acronym>.  Type:
	    <literallayout class="monospaced">
make config CC=<replaceable>path-to-c-compiler</replaceable>	      
	    </literallayout>
	    The above command will print an system architecture
	    string.  Use the architecture string in the following
	    command:
	    <literallayout>
make install arch=<replaceable>arch-string</replaceable>	      
	    </literallayout>
	    The above command will build <acronym>ATLAS</acronym>
	    libraries in directory
	    <filename>ATLAS/lib/<replaceable>arch-string</replaceable></filename>
	    directory.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
      </orderedlist>
    </para>
  </section>

</appendix>